{{Infobox building |image=File:Wheat Street Baptist Church.JPG |caption=Wheat Street Baptist Church seen from the north (back side) |coordinates = {{coord|33.7551682|-84.3756783|display=inline}} |map_type=Atlanta |map_caption = <center>location in [[Intown Atlanta]]</center> | start_date = 1920 | completion_date = 1931 }}
'''Wheat Street Baptist Church''' is located at 359 Auburn Ave. in the [[Sweet Auburn]] neighborhood of [[Atlanta, Georgia]]. The building is part of the [[Martin Luther King, Jr. Historic District]]; the church and its leader at the time, Rev. [[William Holmes Borders]], played a leading role in the [[Civil Rights Movement]].<ref>{{cite book|last=English|first=James W. |title=The prophet of Wheat Street: the story of William Holmes Borders, a man who refused to fail|publisher=D. C. Cook Pub. Co.|year=1967|isbn=978-0-912692-19-7}}</ref> The congregation dates back to 1869, with the present building dating from 1921. From 1898-1929, Rev. [[P. James Bryant]] served as pastor.<ref>[http://wheatstreet.org/?page_id=57 "Our History", 'Wheat Street Baptist Church]</ref>
==References== {{Reflist}} {{Old Fourth Ward}}
[[Category:African-American history in Atlanta]] [[Category:Baptist churches in Georgia (U.S. state)]] [[Category:Movements for civil rights]] [[Category:Old Fourth Ward]] [[Category:Martin Luther King Jr. National Historic Site and Preservation District]] [[Category:Churches completed in 1931]]

{{infobox Museum |name= '''Wile Carding Mill''' |image= WileMill.png |established= 1968 |location= [[Bridgewater, Nova Scotia]], Canada. |type = [[carding]] [[Watermill|mill]], museum |director = |curator = |visitors = |website = [http://cardingmill.novascotia.ca/ cardingmill.novascotia.ca] }}
The '''Wile Carding Mill''' is a defunct but still operational [[carding]] [[Watermill|mill]], in [[Bridgewater, Nova Scotia]], Canada. The mill is now owned by the Province of Nova Scotia and operated as a museum by the [[DesBrisay Museum]].
This water-powered mill was owned and operated by the Wile family from 1860 to 1968. The Wiles ran the mill but employed a number of workers, usually unmarried women, to operate the machinery. The mill was powered by a 7-horsepower (5&nbsp;kW) overshot [[waterwheel]] using the water of Shady Brook, a tributary of the [[Lahave River]].
It became a Registered Heritage Property in Bridgewater in 2013.<ref>{{cite web |last1=de Boer |first1=Laura |title=Wile Carding Mill Museum to become a Registered Heritage Property |url=https://www.industrialheritagens.ca/apps/blog/show/35663379-wile-carding-mill-museum-to-become-a-registered-heritage-property |website=Industrial Heritage Nova Scotia |publisher=IHNS (2013) |accessdate=1 October 2018}}</ref>
